  <static seed="1265" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions10.pg">
    <statement><p>Select all correct simplifications, ignoring possible domain restrictions.</p>
<p><var form="checkboxes">
<li>
<p><m>\frac{4(x-2)}{x -2}=4</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+ 2}{x+2}=1</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{4 x+2}{4}=x+2</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+2}{x}=2</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+2}{2}=x</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{2}{x+2}=\frac{1}{x+1}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{2}{x+2}=\frac{1}{x}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x+2}{x+4}=\frac{2}{4}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{x}{4 x}=\frac{1}{4}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{2 x}{x}=2</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\frac{4 x+2}{x + 2}=4</m></p>
</li>
</var></p>
</statement>
    <solution><p>The correct answer is ABIJ.</p>
<p>We may not cross out common terms when the operation is addition or subtraction. For example, the following is <alert> incorrect </alert>:</p>
<p><m>\frac{1+2}{2+2} = \frac{1}{2}</m> (incorrect)</p>
<p>Otherwise, we are saying <m>\frac{3}{4} = \frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
<p>We may cross out common terms when the operation is multiplication. For example, the following is correct:</p>
<p><m>\frac{2x}{2} = \frac{x}{1} = x</m></p>
<p>We may cross out common factors like <m>x+2</m> when the "major" operation is multiplication. For example, the following is correct:</p>
<p><m>\frac{4(x+2)}{x+2} = \frac{4}{1} = 4</m></p>
</solution>
